the electione and the day of inauguration, the newly elected officials ’ were always given precedence over other senators ot their rank. Hence the consuls-elect were asked for their opinion before the prin— ceps semitis. But, in Cicero’s time, the presiding officer exercised more freedom than formerly, and might invite other men oi consular rank to speak first, if he wished to do them especial honor. During the discussion of any question, a senator might express his own opinion in full (sententiam dicere), or simply assent to some other speaker’s proposal (verbo adsentiri).
